            'This is exactly what the hilsa does, and biologists call it **selective tidal stream transport (STST)**. In tidal rivers like the Padma, the current doesn\'t always flow downstream. Twice a day, the incoming tide pushes sea water upstream \u2014 the **flood tide**. Between the flood tides, the river flows back toward the sea \u2014 the **ebb tide**. The net downstream flow is always present (the river is still a river), but during flood tide, the upstream tidal push partially or fully cancels the downstream river flow.',
            'The hilsa exploits this cycle with a simple but effective strategy. During **flood tide**, when the tidal current pushes upstream and reduces or reverses the net flow, the fish swims actively, riding the favourable current. During **ebb tide**, when the river pushes strongly downstream, the fish drops to the riverbed \u2014 where current speeds are lowest due to friction with the bottom \u2014 and rests. It may shelter behind rocks, in depressions, or in slack-water zones behind bends.',
            'The energy savings are enormous. Studies of migratory fish using STST show that they can cover the same distance while using **40-60% less energy** than fish that swim continuously. Over a 500-kilometre migration during which the fish barely eats, this efficiency is the difference between arriving at the spawning ground with enough energy to reproduce \u2014 or dying of exhaustion along the way. The fishermen of Lakshmikantapur observed this behaviour for centuries: they knew the hilsa ran strongest during flood tides and "rested" during ebb.',
