            'The hilsa does the same thing, but underwater, with far greater sensitivity. Fish don\'t have noses in the human sense, but they have **olfactory pits** \u2014 paired openings on the snout that contain millions of receptor cells bathed in a constant flow of water. These receptors can detect dissolved chemicals at concentrations as low as **parts per billion** \u2014 equivalent to detecting a single drop of perfume dissolved in an Olympic swimming pool.',
            'The theory of olfactory navigation in migratory fish (best studied in salmon, and increasingly supported for hilsa) works like this: when the fish is young, living in its birth river, its developing brain **imprints** on the unique chemical signature of that water. Every river has a distinctive mixture of dissolved minerals (calcium, magnesium, iron), organic compounds (from the specific vegetation and soil of its watershed), and trace elements. This mixture is the river\'s "smell fingerprint."',
