            'This is why tram rails have copper jumper cables bonded across every joint where two sections of rail meet. If even one joint corrodes and loses contact, the return path is broken — just like removing a wire from your torch. The current cannot flow, and the tram stops. Maintaining unbroken electrical continuity across kilometres of rail, through rain, heat, and vibration, is one of the unglamorous but essential engineering challenges of running a tram system.',
