      offlineActivity: 'Demonstrate the quartz inversion concept with ice and a sealed container. Fill a small plastic bottle completely with water, leaving zero air space, and seal the cap tightly. Place it in the freezer for several hours. When the water freezes, it expands by about 9% — far more than the 2% of the quartz inversion, but the principle is identical: a sudden volume change in a confined space creates enormous pressure. The bottle will deform, bulge, or crack. Now imagine this happening inside a clay wall at 573 degrees, with quartz grains expanding suddenly against the surrounding clay. Label one bottle "slow cooling" (place it in the fridge first for a few hours, then the freezer) and one "fast cooling" (straight into the freezer). The fast-cooled bottle is more likely to crack visibly, just as a fast-cooled pot is more likely to crack at the inversion point.',
