            'For a jali screen, this has direct structural implications. The "boundary material" is the stone bridges between openings. Less bridge material means more open area (more light and air passes through) for the same structural strength. A hexagonal jali lets through more light than a square jali with the same bridge width, because hexagons are more efficient at enclosing area with less perimeter. The Pallava carvers may not have known the mathematics, but they knew the result: hexagonal screens were lighter, stronger, and let in more light.',
