      offlineActivity: 'Compare volatile oil loss from whole vs. ground pepper. Take two small jars with lids. In one jar, place a tablespoon of whole black peppercorns. In the other, place a tablespoon of freshly ground pepper from the same batch. Seal both jars, label them with the date, and store them side by side at room temperature. Open each jar and smell it every week for four weeks, rating the aroma intensity on a scale of 1-5. You will observe that the ground pepper loses its aroma noticeably within 1-2 weeks, while the whole peppercorns remain strongly aromatic for the full four weeks. This demonstrates the role of surface area in volatile oil evaporation — the same principle that spice traders exploit by never grinding pepper until the moment of sale.',
